âœ… What Are Anomalies in DBMS?
Anomalies are problems that occur in a database when it is poorly designed (not normalized).
They cause data inconsistency, redundancy, and incorrect behavior during: INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE

Normalization helps remove these anomalies.

â­ Types of Anomalies
There are 3 main anomalies:

1ï¸âƒ£ Update Anomaly
Occurs when the same data exists in multiple places.
If you update one place, you must update all places.
If not, data becomes inconsistent.

âŒ Example (Unnormalized Table)
| StudentID | StudentName | Course | Instructor |
| --------- | ----------- | ------ | ---------- |
| 1         | Suyog       | DBMS   | Mehta      |
| 2         | Rohan       | SQL    | Mehta      |

Instructor "Mehta" repeated twice.

Problem
If instructor name changes to â€œMehta Sirâ€, YOU MUST update both rows.
If you forget one â†’ inconsistent data.

ğŸ‘‰ This is Update Anomaly.



2ï¸âƒ£ Insert Anomaly
Occurs when you cannot insert data because some other data is missing.

âŒ Example
You want to add a new course "AI" with instructor "Kapoor".
But your table structure is:

| StudentID | StudentName | Course | Instructor |

You cannot insert a course until a student registers for it.

ğŸ‘‰ This is Insert Anomaly.



3ï¸âƒ£ Delete Anomaly
Occurs when deleting one record unintentionally removes other important data.

âŒ Example
| StudentID | StudentName | Course | Instructor |
| --------- | ----------- | ------ | ---------- |
| 1         | Suyog       | DBMS   | Mehta      |

If you delete Suyog (the only student in DBMS),
then DBMS + Instructor Mehta data also gets deleted.

So deleting one fact removes another fact.

ğŸ‘‰ This is Delete Anomaly.


ğŸ§  Summary Table
Anomaly Type	When it Occurs	Problem
Update	Same data stored multiple times	Data inconsistency
Insert	Cannot insert data without other data	Missing information
Delete	Deleting a record removes needed data	Loss of information


ğŸ¯ Why Anomalies Occur?
Because table is poorly structured:
Repeating groups
Redundant data
Dependencies not organized
Not normalized

Thus, database becomes inconsistent.


ğŸ”¥ How to Remove Anomalies?

Apply Normalization:
1NF â†’ Remove repeating groups
2NF â†’ Remove partial dependency
3NF â†’ Remove transitive dependency
BCNF â†’ Solve advanced anomalies


ğŸ“Œ Interview Answer (Short & Crisp)

Anomalies are problems in database operations caused by un-normalized tables. The three main anomalies are:
Update anomaly â€“ updating data in one place but not in others leads to inconsistency.
Insert anomaly â€“ cannot insert a record because some required data is missing.
Delete anomaly â€“ deleting a record unintentionally deletes important information.

Normalization helps eliminate these anomalies.



